WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:00.270
[Music]

00:00:00.270 --> 00:00:13.170
Good day, I'm Norman Wildberger. In the last few&nbsp;
videos, we've been talking about positive poly&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:13.170 --> 00:00:19.230
numbers, or we might just say poly numbers&nbsp;
for short. These are fundamental building&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:19.230 --> 00:00:26.160
blocks for algebra, and the way I want you to&nbsp;
think about them is that they are extensions&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:26.160 --> 00:00:33.060
of ordinary numbers or more sophisticated&nbsp;
versions of numbers. If you look at the way&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:33.060 --> 00:00:40.530
we add two positive poly numbers or the way we&nbsp;
multiply them, if you just look at the top level,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:40.530 --> 00:00:47.430
the zero-degree terms, then you just have ordinary&nbsp;
addition of numbers or ordinary multiplication of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:47.430 --> 00:00:53.490
numbers. So at the top level, at degree zero, we&nbsp;
are just getting ordinary arithmetic, and what&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:53.490 --> 00:00:59.160
happens below is some kind of sophisticated or&nbsp;
more fancy arithmetic that's built up from it.

00:00:59.160 --> 00:01:08.520
Today let's start off by talking about another&nbsp;
operation: the idea of multiplying a polynomial to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:08.520 --> 00:01:15.150
give us another poly number. For example, here is&nbsp;
a poly number: (2, 3) multiplied by the ordinary&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:15.150 --> 00:01:22.860
number 5 gives us the poly number (10, 15).&nbsp;
The rule is simply that you take a poly number,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:22.860 --> 00:01:29.910
multiply it by m, a number, and you get the&nbsp;
new poly number whose entries are multiplied&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:29.910 --> 00:01:38.550
by m. So we're scaling the poly number, and&nbsp;
this operation has some obvious properties:&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:39.120 --> 00:01:46.110
if you have two poly numbers P and Q and you&nbsp;
take m times (P + Q), you get mP + mQ. If you&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:46.110 --> 00:01:50.850
have two numbers m and n and you multiply&nbsp;
a poly number P first by n and then by m,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:50.850 --> 00:01:58.200
it's the same as multiplying P by the&nbsp;
product mn. And if we have m times (P&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:58.200 --> 00:02:05.700
times Q) where P and Q are both poly numbers,&nbsp;
that's the same as (mP) times Q, which is also&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:05.700 --> 00:02:11.520
the same as P times (mQ) (I didn't have room&nbsp;
to write it). So this is a useful additional&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:11.520 --> 00:02:18.630
operation that involves not just poly numbers&nbsp;
but also numbers as well. We should be careful&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:18.630 --> 00:02:23.370
to distinguish between poly numbers and ordinary&nbsp;
numbers; technically, they're different objects.

00:02:23.370 --> 00:02:29.730
This idea of scaling poly numbers gives us an&nbsp;
alternative way of thinking about multiplying&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:29.730 --> 00:02:37.260
two poly numbers, which makes it very parallel&nbsp;
to Hindu-Arabic multiplication. For example,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:37.260 --> 00:02:45.060
if you're multiplying (2, 3) by (1, 0, 4), the&nbsp;
result, which is over here (2, 3, 0, 12), can also&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:45.060 --> 00:02:52.140
be obtained by taking this one and multiplying it&nbsp;
first by (2, 0, 0), giving us (2, 0, 8), and then&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:52.140 --> 00:02:58.230
multiplying it by (0, 3), which has the effect&nbsp;
of multiplying each of the entries by 3 and also&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:58.230 --> 00:03:05.550
shifting everything down one. So we've got 2 times&nbsp;
(1, 0, 4) plus 3 times the shifted-down (1, 0, 4).

00:03:05.550 --> 00:03:09.570
Why is that the same as Hindu-Arabic&nbsp;
multiplication? Well, suppose we wanted&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:09.570 --> 00:03:18.870
to multiply the numbers 401, which is one read up,&nbsp;
times this number 32. In ordinary multiplication,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:18.870 --> 00:03:27.120
we would use this 2 and multiply by 401 to give us&nbsp;
802, and then we would multiply by 3 (which is 0,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:27.120 --> 00:03:31.560
12) and shift everything over one because&nbsp;
we're actually multiplying by something&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:31.560 --> 00:03:41.160
in the tens spot. Then we add the ones,&nbsp;
tens, hundreds, and thousands. Normally,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:41.160 --> 00:03:49.230
there being 12 here is not allowed; we would&nbsp;
ordinarily carry something over to the next spot,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:49.230 --> 00:03:54.960
but in this setup, what we're going to&nbsp;
do is just allow the entries of each&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:54.960 --> 00:04:02.850
position to be arbitrary natural numbers, not&nbsp;
restricted from 0 to 9. So that's essentially&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:02.850 --> 00:04:06.390
what we're doing when we're doing this&nbsp;
kind of multiplication. We're just doing&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:06.390 --> 00:04:13.530
Hindu-Arabic multiplication allowing&nbsp;
arbitrary numbers in each of the slots.

00:04:15.870 --> 00:04:19.590
Here's another example: you can check&nbsp;
that, say, (3, 2, 5) times (1, 4,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:19.590 --> 00:04:26.790
0) is obtained by first multiplying this by&nbsp;
3, multiplying it by 2 and shifting down,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:27.450 --> 00:04:37.650
multiplying this by 5 and shifting down two, and&nbsp;
then adding all the way across like that. Here's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:37.650 --> 00:04:46.260
a very easy example with a special poly number&nbsp;
(0, 1), just noting that its effect on another&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:46.260 --> 00:04:52.710
poly number is simply to shift it down one.&nbsp;
This poly number is the simplest poly number&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:52.710 --> 00:04:57.570
which is not itself essentially a number, and it's&nbsp;
going to play an important role as we carry on.

00:04:57.570 --> 00:05:04.920
Now let's talk about associativity of&nbsp;
multiplication. Suppose we have three&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:04.920 --> 00:05:13.530
poly numbers P, Q, and R with entries p_i,&nbsp;
q_i, and r_i. The product PQ is another poly&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:13.530 --> 00:05:21.000
number whose i-th entry is given by this formula:&nbsp;
the sum over all k's and l's, positive numbers,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:21.000 --> 00:05:32.910
of p_k times q_l where k + l sum to i. Alright,&nbsp;
so now suppose we have these three poly numbers,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:32.910 --> 00:05:40.230
we multiply them all together in the order PQ and&nbsp;
then R. Well, the i-th entry of that is, according&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:40.230 --> 00:05:49.950
to this rule, the sum over all k and l where k + l&nbsp;
equals i of the k-th entry of P times Q times the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:49.950 --> 00:05:58.200
l-th entry of R. Now, what's inside here itself&nbsp;
is going to be replaced by this thing right here:&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:59.070 --> 00:06:08.910
the sum over all, say, n and m summing to k of&nbsp;
p_n times q_m. So this is a double summation,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:08.910 --> 00:06:15.060
a little bit complicated. But when you stare&nbsp;
at it, you really have these three numbers n,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:15.060 --> 00:06:22.110
m, and l, and they have the property&nbsp;
that they add up to i. We're really&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:22.110 --> 00:06:30.090
multiplying p_n times q_m times r_l over all such&nbsp;
possibilities. When we've written it this way,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:30.090 --> 00:06:35.790
we see that it's now symmetric; it'll be the same&nbsp;
as what we get when we expand this thing out:&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:35.790 --> 00:06:45.980
P times (QR)'s i component. That's essentially a&nbsp;
sketch of the proof of why associativity works.

00:06:47.060 --> 00:06:53.060
To give you a sense of what this formula means,&nbsp;
let's have a look at a few examples. Here we're&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:53.060 --> 00:07:01.070
multiplying three poly numbers: (1, 2) times (2,&nbsp;
5) times (4, 3). That formula that we had at the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:01.070 --> 00:07:08.570
end of the last slide tells us the way we do this&nbsp;
as follows: to find the 0th entry of the result,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:08.570 --> 00:07:17.180
we take the product of all the entries whose&nbsp;
indices sum up to 0, and there's only one way&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:17.180 --> 00:07:24.410
of doing that: it's the 0 plus 0 plus 0 makes&nbsp;
0. So there's 1 times 2 times 4; we get 8. To&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:24.410 --> 00:07:29.630
get the first entry, we have to look at products&nbsp;
of three things: one from here, one from here,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:29.630 --> 00:07:41.090
one from here so that the sum of the indices is&nbsp;
one. That could be 0, 0, 1, or it could be 0, 1,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:41.090 --> 00:07:48.440
0, or it could be 1, 0, 0. There are the three&nbsp;
products that we have to add up correspondingly,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:48.440 --> 00:08:00.020
giving us 42. The second-degree term is obtained&nbsp;
by taking products of three things so that the sum&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:00.020 --> 00:08:08.480
of the indices is now 2. That can be obtained&nbsp;
by taking 1 times 5 times 3 (that's degree 0,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:08.480 --> 00:08:15.560
that's degree 1, that's degree 1, so that has a&nbsp;
total degree of 2 when we multiply), or we could&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:15.560 --> 00:08:23.870
take 2 times 2 times 3, or we could take 4 times&nbsp;
2 times 5. We add those three possibilities up;&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:23.870 --> 00:08:29.780
we get 67. Finally, the degree 3 term:&nbsp;
there's only one way of getting a degree&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:29.780 --> 00:08:37.610
3 term, which is to take the degree 1 term times&nbsp;
the degree 1 term times the degree 1 term. This&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:37.610 --> 00:08:42.890
product that we've just done corresponds&nbsp;
to the usual kind of polynomial product:&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:42.890 --> 00:08:49.940
multiply (1 + 2x) times (2 + 5x) times (4 +&nbsp;
3x), and we're getting that polynomial there.

00:08:51.500 --> 00:08:55.310
Here's another example that you can check&nbsp;
the details to make sure you understand how&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:55.310 --> 00:09:01.310
this procedure works. So now that we've&nbsp;
got some familiarity with poly numbers,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:01.310 --> 00:09:06.620
it's time for us to say now exactly&nbsp;
what is a polynomial. We'll do that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:06.620 --> 00:09:12.170
next time. I hope you'll join me for that. I'm&nbsp;
Norman Wildberger, and thanks for listening.

00:09:12.170 --> 00:09:12.230
[Music]

